# Binary Trees in Java

Picture a family tree upside-down: one root at the top, each node has at most two children (left and right), and every node except the root has exactly one parent. There are no cycles. This shape makes recursion feel natural — almost every tree problem solves itself once you ask: 'What should I do at *this* node, and what should I ask my children?'

## Node definition and shape intuition
```java
class TreeNode {
    int val;
    TreeNode left, right;
    TreeNode(int val) { this.val = val; }
}

// Visual:
//        4          ← root (depth 0)
//       / \
//      2   6        ← depth 1
//     / \ / \
//    1  3 5  7      ← depth 2 (leaves)
```

## The four traversals — when does each node get visited?
```java
// IN-order   (Left → Root → Right)  → sorted output for BST
// PRE-order   (Root → Left → Right)  → copy/serialise tree
// POST-order  (Left → Right → Root)  → delete tree, calc subtree sizes
// LEVEL-order (BFS, level by level)  → find depth, zigzag print

void inorder(TreeNode n) {
    if (n == null) return;
    inorder(n.left);
    visit(n);         // ← comes BETWEEN children → sorted
    inorder(n.right);
}
void preorder(TreeNode n) {
    if (n == null) return;
    visit(n);         // ← comes BEFORE children → root first
    preorder(n.left);
    preorder(n.right);
}
void postorder(TreeNode n) {
    if (n == null) return;
    postorder(n.left);
    postorder(n.right);
    visit(n);         // ← comes AFTER children → bottom-up
}
```

## Height and diameter — the two most common recursive patterns
```java
// HEIGHT: longest path from node down to any leaf
int height(TreeNode n) {
    if (n == null) return -1;  // empty tree height = -1
    return 1 + Math.max(height(n.left), height(n.right));
}

// DIAMETER: longest path between ANY two nodes (may not pass through root)
// Key insight: at each node, the best path through it = leftHeight + rightHeight + 2
int maxDiameter = 0;
int diameter(TreeNode n) {
    if (n == null) return -1;
    int l = diameter(n.left),  r = diameter(n.right);
    maxDiameter = Math.max(maxDiameter, l + r + 2);  // path through n
    return 1 + Math.max(l, r);  // return height to parent
}
```

## BST properties — the sorted invariant
```java
// A BST satisfies: for every node N,
//   ALL values in left subtree  < N.val
//   ALL values in right subtree > N.val
//
// Visual BST:         8
//                   /   \
//                  3     10
//                 / \      \
//                1   6      14
//                   / \
//                  4   7
//
// In-order traversal → [1, 3, 4, 6, 7, 8, 10, 14]  ← always sorted!

// Validate BST: pass down min/max bounds
boolean isValid(TreeNode n, long min, long max) {
    if (n == null) return true;
    if (n.val <= min || n.val >= max) return false;
    return isValid(n.left, min, n.val)
        && isValid(n.right, n.val, max);
}
```

## Lowest Common Ancestor (LCA)
```java
// LCA of p and q = deepest node that has BOTH p and q in its subtree.
//
// Mental model: imagine two people climbing up the tree independently.
// The first node where their paths MERGE is the LCA.
//
// Recursive intuition:
//   • If current node IS p or q → return it (it could be LCA itself)
//   • Search left subtree, search right subtree
//   • If BOTH sides return non-null → current node is LCA
//   • Otherwise → return whichever side found something
TreeNode lca(TreeNode root, TreeNode p, TreeNode q) {
    if (root == null || root == p || root == q) return root;
    TreeNode left  = lca(root.left,  p, q);
    TreeNode right = lca(root.right, p, q);
    if (left != null && right != null) return root;  // split here
    return left != null ? left : right;
}
```

## Level-order — BFS on a tree gives you depth information for free
```java
List<List<Integer>> levelOrder(TreeNode root) {
    List<List<Integer>> res = new ArrayList<>();
    if (root == null) return res;
    Queue<TreeNode> q = new ArrayDeque<>();
    q.offer(root);
    while (!q.isEmpty()) {
        int sz = q.size();          // nodes on THIS level
        List<Integer> level = new ArrayList<>();
        for (int i = 0; i < sz; i++) {
            TreeNode n = q.poll();
            level.add(n.val);
            if (n.left  != null) q.offer(n.left);
            if (n.right != null) q.offer(n.right);
        }
        res.add(level);
    }
    return res;
}
```

## Common Pitfalls
- Not checking null before accessing node.left or node.right
- Height vs depth confusion: height counts edges DOWN from a node; depth counts edges UP from root
- Diameter problem: forgetting to track a global max — the best diameter may not pass through the root
- BST validation: checking only the immediate parent is wrong — you must propagate the valid range (min/max bounds) down
- LCA on BST: simpler O(log n) version exists (walk left if both < root, right if both > root) — use it when the tree is confirmed BST

## Connections
- **Recursion**: tree problems ARE recursion — almost always base case = null node
- **Queues**: level-order traversal is BFS using a queue
- **Arrays**: in-order of BST produces a sorted array — connect to searching/sorting
- **Graphs**: a tree is a connected acyclic undirected graph — tree algorithms generalise to graphs
